  <title>Executing Two Instances</title>
  <keywords>
    <keyword>concurrent instances</keyword>
    <keyword>ds10_flash.rom</keyword>
    <keyword>EMULATR_CONSOLE_PORT</keyword>
    <keyword>EMULATR_FLASH_ROM</keyword>
    <keyword>flash corruption</keyword>
    <keyword>flash isolation</keyword>
    <keyword>NVRAM</keyword>
    <keyword>snapshots</keyword>
    <keyword>two instances</keyword>
  </keywords>
  <body>
    <header><para styleclass="Heading1">Executing Two Instances</para></header>
    <para styleclass="Normal">Two instances launched from the same directory share <text styleclass="Code Example">ds10_flash.rom</text> and the <text styleclass="Code Example">snapshots/</text> directory, and concurrent NVRAM writes can corrupt the flash. Give each console its own port with <text styleclass="Code Example">EMULATR_CONSOLE_PORT</text>, and if a run will write NVRAM (any <text styleclass="Code Example">set</text> or <text styleclass="Code Example">update</text> at the <text styleclass="Code Example">&gt;&gt;&gt;</text> prompt), isolate its flash first.</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example">cp ds10_flash.rom ds10_flash_release.rom</para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example"># then prepend on the launch line:  EMULATR_FLASH_ROM=ds10_flash_release.rom</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal">With a separate <text styleclass="Code Example">EMULATR_FLASH_ROM</text> per instance, NVRAM writes no longer collide. Confirm the second instance came up on its own port by checking its log for "Listening on TCP port 10024".</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="SeeAlso">See Also.</text></para>
